title: (n,n+gamma) reactions in natural chromium

x4codes.hlp: Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE), Aldermaston, United Kingdom

x4freetext: (n,n+gamma) reactions in natural chromium

x4codes.hlp: Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE), Aldermaston, United Kingdom

x4freetext: AWRE 6 MV Van de Graaff accelerator.
T(p,n)-reaction, using a 2.5 cm long gas cell
target with a 3.5 mg/cm2 Mo entrance foil filled
to 760 torr.
The energy spread of neutrons at the scatterer
was approximately 70 keV at 0.55 MeV, 50 keV at
1.0 MeV and 40 keV at 3.85 MeV, largely due to proton
energy loss, in the gas cell.
Time of flight. Ring geometry.
Two series of measurement have been performed.
The excitation functions
of the 1434 keV gamma-rays were used to put the two
series on the same scale for all gamma-ray energies.
The gamma-ray energies are averages of values deduced
from 3 series I and 3 series II runs where each run
has been individually calibrated by reference to
standard impurity peaks such as the beta+ annihilation
peak(2223.3 keV) present in all spectra.
Individual gamma-ray energy error is estimated
as +-1 keV.
The net count in each gamma-ray peak was found by
subtraction of a background estimated by averaging
the background levels on either side of the peak.
* In series I of experiments Cr powder in thin-walled
Al torus of rectangular cross-section was used.
The actual Cr scatterer was 14.8 cm outer diam.,
10.5 cm inner diam.,  3.5 cm long and of mass 1128 g.
* In series II of experiments sintered chromium ring
of 13.2 cm outer diam., 10.2 cm inner diam.,
length 1.5 cm and mass 476 g.
Better than 99.5% purity in both cases.
Two Ge(Li) detectors.
* In I series of experiments detector was of the
planar  drifted type with ~2.5 cm3 sensitive volume.
* In II series of experiments detector was
coaxially drifted, of ~20. cm3 sensitive volume.
A mean relative angle of 100 deg. is taken as emission
angle of gamma rays between 80. and 120. degr.
relative to the mean incident neutron direction.
Long counter for the neutron monitor at 90.degr
Gammas.
Corrected for multiple inelastic scattering.
The errors quoted for cross sections are one
standard deviation and are a combination in quadrature
of the following contributions:
* Statistical errors
Uncertainty due to PHA dead-time correction
Uncertainty due to Ge(Li) counter efficiency
at one energy relative to another
Uncertainty due to scatterer self-absorption
correction
Uncertainty in long counter efficiency
Uncertainty in ratio of T(p,n) differential
cross sections at 10. and 90. degr.
From authors: Since no absolute cross section
measurements were available from the neutron
time-af-flight spectrometer in this laboratory with
which to compare our results we present only relative
excitation cross sections, at a mean scattering angle
of 100. degr.
